    Ans: Research Question- What is the relationship between the number of confirmed deaths and the number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Massachusetts on a weekly basis?

  4. Based on the research question you proposed above, propose a hypothesis about a possible relationship between two items. (5%)

    Ans: Hypothesis- I hypothesize that there is a positive relationship between the number of confirmed deaths and the number of confirmed cases. As the number of confirmed cases increases, the number of confirmed deaths will also increase and vice-versa.

  5. Based on the hypothesis proposed, please select variables/columns in the data to measure the corresponding concepts in the hypothesis statement. You should select at least one variable/column to measure each concept.

    You should also specify which variables/columns you choose and explain why they are the proper ones to measure the concepts. (10%)

    Instruction: Donât just answer, âThey are reliable and validâ. Instead, you should discuss more why they are reliable (can consistently produce the same results regardless of the same results regardless different times and contexts) and valid (why it is better than other possible or alternative variables/columns). You can find the concepts of validity and reliability in the Nov 20 lecture and the slides (p23-25). There are also more in-depth introductions online, such as this page.

    Ans : Variables/Columns to Measure Concepts:

    • Dependent Variable (DV): Number of Confirmed Deaths

    • Independent Variable (IV): Number of Confirmed Cases

    Explanation of Reliability and Validity -

    • For Confirmed Deaths:

      • Reliability: The reliability of the âConfirmed deathsâ variable can be justified by its consistent reporting over time. Deaths due to COVID-19 are typically accurately recorded, and this information is less likely to vary between different times and contexts.

      • Validity: The validity of the âConfirmed deathsâ variable is supported by the fact that it directly measures the outcome of interest, which is the number of deaths attributed to COVID-19. This is a direct and accurate representation of the concept it intends to measure.

    • For Confirmed Cases:

      • Reliability: As per defination, consistent in producing the same results every time the measure is used. Hence, it is reliable because it consistently reports the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases over time.

      • Validity: Again, as per defination, it is measuring what is supposed to measure. Hence, it is valid as it directly measures the concept of interest, representing the spread of the virus in the population.

  6. Use the code we learned in the previous week to conduct descriptive statistics for the two variables/columns you selected above. You should present the following information in your descriptive statistics: range, average, standard deviation, the number of NAs, and the number of unique values. (5%)

    sum_stat <- function(x){
  stat <- tibble(
range=range(x, na.rm = T),
mean=mean(x, na.rm = T),
sd=sd(x,na.rm=T),
na = sum(is.na(x)),
unique = length(unique(x))
  )
  return(stat)
}
    #type your code here
    sum_stat(ma_covid19$`Confirmed deaths`)
    sum_stat(ma_covid19$`Confirmed cases`)

The scatter plot visually displays the relationship between confirmed cases and confirmed deaths. From the scatter plot, we could see that data is scattered and right skewed as seen from the histogram. Further, The positive correlation coefficient suggests a weak positive linear relationship between the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases and the number of confirmed deaths in Massachusetts. As the number of confirmed cases increases, there is a tendency for the number of confirmed deaths to also increase. However, the correlation is not very strong (correlation coefficient around 0.336), indicating that other factors may contribute to the number of deaths.

Part 2. Reviewing the findings of a graph by examining the raw data. (50%)

This part of the challenge is based on a scenario. Suppose you are a data scientist who provides consulting services to the government. One day, your client asks you to investigate an article by the New York Times that reported on some research on peopleâs confidence in the institutions of democracy. It had been published in an academic journal. The headline in the Times ran, âHow Stable Are Democracies? âWarning Signs Are Flashing Redââ (Taub, 2016). The graph accompanying the article, as shown below, plots peopleâs responses to a question in the World Value Survey (WVS) (V162-Importance of democracy). The graph certainly seemed to show an alarming decline. The graph was widely circulated on social media. Itâs an elegant small-multiple that, in addition to the point ranges it identifies, also shows an error range (labeled as such for people who might not know what it is), and the story told across the panels for each country is pretty consistent.

  1. Please briefly describe the major findings of this graph. (5%)

Ans: As the article consists peopleâs responses on their views of living in a democracy. The graph consists data from six countries - Sweden, Australia, Netherlands, United States, New Zealand, and Britain. As we could see that the graph is of declining nature over the years for each country suggesting peopleâs negative view of living in a democracy. Now, the data is from period 1930 to 1980 for every country. For period 1930 to 1940, the most decline is in Britain and least on Netherlands. The possible reason could be larger population of Britain and it is more advanced then Netherlands. Similarly, 1970s to 1980s, the most decline is in United States, considering the population and advancement of freedom of views or more liberal view equally supported from growth of technology and media. Overall, we could see that big nations in terms of area or population like United States and Britain respectively, we have higher decline ratio then country like Netherlands, where there is not much striking change between two 10 years. For all countries, the lowest is at 1970-80, due to the fact of growth of liberal mindset and more advancement in general. For Britain, there is slight increase of positive response from the people from 1940-60, the reason could be increasing migration of people from countries like India or Pakistan.

Overall for all countries (except Netherland - above 50% for the 30s generation, and about 30% for the 80s generation ) we could say, there is a decline in the proportion of population above 70% of the 30s generation to less than 50% of the 80s generation (except Sweden).

  1. Your client is concerned about the findings of this graph. On the one hand, they are surprised and worried by the âcrisis of democracyâ presented in this graph.On the other hand, they also doubt the argument of the NYT article and the validity of the findings of this graph. Before deciding on making any policy to respond, they ask you to conduct some additional research with the original data.

summary_stats <- function(x){
  stat <- tibble(
range=range(x, na.rm = T),
mean=mean(x, na.rm = T),
sd=sd(x,na.rm=T), 
na = sum(x < 0), #should be cautious that NA in the dataset is noted as negative numbers.
unique = length(unique(x))
  )
  return(stat)
}

library(ggplot2)

wvs_plot <- wvs_data |> 
mutate(Decade_of_Birth = V236 %/% 10*10,
   dem_importance = as.numeric(V162),
   countries = as.numeric(V2))


final_plot <- wvs_plot %>% 
group_by(countries, Decade_of_Birth) |> 
summarise(Average = mean(dem_importance)) |>
 mutate(countries = recode(countries,
                   "752" = "Sweden",
                   "554" = "NewZealand",
                   "36"  = "Australia",
                   "528" = "Netherland",
                   "840" = "UnitedStates",
                   "826" = "UnitedKingdom")) |> 
ggplot(aes(x = as.numeric(Decade_of_Birth), y = Average))+
geom_smooth()+
geom_point()+
scale_x_continuous(limits = c(1930,1980))+

theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))+
facet_grid(~ countries)

  2. Describe what you find from the graph you made above. Compared to the graph on NYT, whatâs in common, or whatâs different? Please type your answer below. (5%)

    Ans: Description of the graph: This graph shows the relationship between the decades of birth (x-axis) and the average level of response scores to the question âimportance of democracyâ (y-axis) for each of the six countries. As we could see from the above plots, that for countries like Australia, Britain and United States, there is significant decline in overall average response of the people for âImportance of Democracyâ. Here, United States shows more decline than others. Whereas, countries like Sweden and Netherlands, have smaller decline or increment in given time periods. In comparison with NYT Graph:

    • Similarity: Countries like United States and United Kingdom has steep drop than relatively stable like Netherland or Sweden. We can also observe a decline of the average score of the imporance of democracy from above 8.5/10 among the older generation (30s) to 7.0/10 among the younger generation (80s).

    • Differences: New Zealand is totally different in both. In the later graph, the survey seems to be missing. For year, 1970-80, Sweden seems to have more average response than in NYT graph.   3. Your client wants to hear your conclusion. Do you agree with the argument presented by the graph and the NYT article? Should we really worry about the decline? This is an op-ed question. Please type your answer below. (5%)

    Ans: Yes, looking into both the graphâs we can conclude that peopleâs response is declining over the years about the âimportance of democracyâ. Yes, decline in democracy seems to be concerning. Democracy is often considered a fundamental aspect of a just and equitable society. A decline in its perceived importance may suggest a shift in public attitudes, which could have implications for civic engagement, political participation, and the overall health of democratic institutions. It may be worth exploring the reasons behind this decline and addressing any underlying issues that contribute to it. On the other hand, fluctuations in public opinion are not uncommon, and various factors can influence peopleâs perceptions at different points in time. Itâs essential to critically examine the methodology used in the survey, consider cultural and contextual factors, and assess whether the decline is a temporary trend or a more sustained shift. Additionally, public opinion is dynamic and can be influenced by external events, economic conditions, or political developments.
